Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law introducing administrative liability for violating the time and procedure for payment of goods (work, services) in procurement for State and municipal needs.
The purpose of the Act is to address the very acute problem of the failure of customers to comply with their obligations in public and municipal procurement.
As early as two years ago, it was common for entrepreneurs to be unable to obtain payment under public and municipal contracts already executed.
At the same time, the President of the Russian Federation instructed the Office of the Procurator-General of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because businessmen themselves were unable to deal with unscrupulous customers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried their best to avoid payment obligations and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in general in the country.
Since 2015, in order to protect the right of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office has submitted 9,700 submissions, disciplinary proceedings have been brought against 4,500 officials, administrative proceedings have been instituted against 533 officials, and criminal proceedings have been instituted against 46 of them.
As a result, more than 66 billion roubles were owed to entrepreneurs.
These huge amounts were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs, far more modest amounts, have led to huge debts.
Here's a special case.
The head of a small company won a multi-million ruble social transport competition.
The man invested all his working capital, fully discharged his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is an increasing financial pool of debt on wages, taxes, loans that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought the assistance of the Public Prosecutor's Office.
The problem has now been minimized in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total debt on State and municipal contracts, as identified by the procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to approximately 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the Office of the Public Prosecutor operates under a manual crisis management regime.
The Attorney-General personally holds mobile meetings with the local authorities, at which all violations discovered by the prosecutors are dealt with in a meaningful manner and measures are taken to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place this year in Yaroslav and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Act No. 189-FZ “On amendments to the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with regard to the establishment of administrative liability of the officials of the employer for violation of the time and procedure for payment of goods (work, services) in procurement to meet State and municipal needs”, signed last week by the President of Russia, will improve the payment discipline of public customers in a qualitative manner.
The draft law was drafted by the Ministry of Development of Russia on the initiative of the Office of the Procurator-General.
The new law would supplement the Code of Administrative Offences with an article providing for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 roubles for the violation by an official of the employer of the time limit and the procedure for paying goods, work and services in State and municipal procurement.
If an official has already been subjected to an administrative penalty for a similar offence, he or she will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are implemented in practice.
Civil Rights Unit has issued a warning on movement to Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to coloured people travelling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads as follows: “The warning to travellers of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, valid until 28 August 2017, calls upon African American travellers, visitors and citizens of the state of Missouri to be particularly attentive and to exercise great caution when travelling in the state in connection with a number of suspicious racist incidents that have recently taken place throughout the state and that have taken place here.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the recent Missouri law, which made it more difficult for people to win claims of discrimination, led to the fact that State law enforcement agencies disproportionately target minority groups.
“In your people, human rights are violated.
They are stopped on the roads because of their colour, beaten and killed,” says the newspaper Cansas City Star, Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri.
“We hear complaints more often than ever.”
This is the first warning of its kind announced by the organization vis-à-vis the U.S. state.
The Panel referred to incidents such as the humiliation of black students on racial grounds at the University of Missouri and the death of Tori Sanders, a twenty-eight-year-old man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas on a trip to the state, and the Missouri state police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report from the Missouri State Attorney General's Office, according to which black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues of what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People must be trained in one way or another to take the bail money with them or to inform their relatives that they are travelling across state territory.”
According to the latest FBI hate crime reporting program, there were 100 hate crimes recorded in Missouri in 2015, making the state the sixteenth largest hate crime in the state.
The travel notice is also a response to the new Missouri law, which will make it more difficult to bring a case against a legal person for housing or labour discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had issued warnings to travellers in Texas and Arizona after those states had enacted new immigration control laws requiring local law enforcement authorities to arrest people for immigration offences, which ACLU believed would increase the number of racial audits.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the Department of State for other countries, but more recently, public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
