As Miller grumbled at Acosta, "I don't want to go into history here, but the Statue of Freedom is... a symbol of American freedom that shines the world.
The poem you're talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller was right about the facts, but like he said, it's not really about history.
It's about the current sound of the amazing words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming of a free breath, / the unhappy waste of your abundant shores."
Never before have the "unfortunate scum" been so visible on our screens.
Miller didn't do literature, he made it clear that Trump wasn't expecting these people in America.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to place her words on the basement of the statue after her death - knew very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The design of the sculpture was to mark the link between the French and American republics through a banal classic figure, the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of a poem and an image was a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack against American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right, though, changed it back.
Rash Limbo, a kind of John the Baptizer who announced Trump's arrival in 2010, argued that freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neo-conservator carrying America's flame to the darkness of the world: “Freedom goes forward.
