Blocking critics on Facebook: don't run for public office unless you're ready to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
The Americans loved George Washington, but that did not prevent them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Of course, his criticism was annoying.
But he didn't shut his mouth to his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "It's possible to take away the freedom of speech and lead us deaf and dumb to slaughter."
Now I'm going to go to the Governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and erased at least 450 people who expressed their views on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "what and what."
"It's just Facebook," a lot of people will say.
But it's important, too.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's an amazingly popular Republican governor in a state-based democracy.
He's second in the approval rating among the country's 50 governors.
Hogan's not a stubborn reactionary.
He has shown a strong hand in the management of the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also uses Facebook cleverly as a primary way of communicating with his constituents and shows his bald head on his page after chemotherapy.
It is therefore unnecessary and ultimately harmful to block people who come to the Governor ' s page, which is declared an official public forum and is run by the administration with taxpayer money.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokesperson Amelia Ches defended the Governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was just a recapitulation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spamers, and haters on the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are the real people, not trolls, the teacher, the businessman, the pastor, who turn to their elected leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, informative, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, arguing that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed at his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the comment section on the post.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same subject, some people say right away that it's a so-called loop instead of admitting they're dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens."
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call a "active life stance."
In the Facebook era, it is easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is far less dusty than before when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical front lines, or arresting and silenced protesters.
But that's exactly what's going on right now, just in the figure.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users, who have been covered in his Twitter account.
One of the first, turning points on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Kasheris of Alexandria, the Chairman of the Laudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by turning the voter over on her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, the Republican Governor Matt Bavin was challenged by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behaviour on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington, D.C., the era of affordable postal spending was a coup d’état similar to today’s Internet.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers increased fourfold, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
And even then Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the alias "Yuricola", "Valerios", "Belizarius" and "Porzius" wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by George Washington's online paper project, his office was overwhelmed by petitions critical of his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn't try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lie at the very heart of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting it.
