Poverty and Death in Indonesia’s Golden Land
Bardin Deguei doesn't use the stove when he's making dinner.
She doesn't even use the pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the mutinous Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply puts sweet potatoes, which are called "nota", right in the fireplace.
After half an hour, a charred tuber is drawn and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Deguei sits on the ground floor – she has no furniture – and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
The bathroom is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She's the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she wasn't assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one decides to walk in the village after five p.m.”, she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, the former Dutch colony that was joined to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote in public in front of the occupying forces.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta Government, which retains strong control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders from being allowed.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent State of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as an abandoned city; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the capital of the province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour shake in a hired car.
There's no public transport here.
