"It's a stain on our history and it's a stone on our souls."
Seventy-one-year-old Brooks is a former member of Georgia's Congress who has spent his entire life fighting for human rights.
To him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want investigations, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We cannot proceed to healing and reconciliation until we have justice."
The Coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the Morse Ford lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI material received by NBC News, more than 50 individuals in Monroe and neighbouring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although suspects have been at large for decades, human rights defenders say that the city has always been well aware of two related motives of vigilantes: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ' s ruling first allowed black citizens to vote on the primaries that were to take place that summer.
About the same election, according to the FBI, Black source Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, apparently because of a woman, in a fight.
Brooks says that according to rumours around town, Hester slept with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the child she was supposed to have was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 in bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove out of prison and drove to the Morse Ford Bridge, a crowd of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that he organized and commanded Harrison's murders," that's what one of the FBI's reports concludes.
"It is also clear that there was a conspiracy between state and city law enforcement agencies not only to take part in the murders, but also to destroy evidence and conceal the identity of witnesses."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt on electoral rights," he says.
"They were all killed to send a signal to black people in town: if you register and vote, you'll be the same."
For almost ten years, Cassandra Greene has been running an annual play that reproduces that lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visible, he captures the audience and tells of the deep racism that many would like to think is no longer in America.
It's hard to look at, and it's harder to turn around, but Green thinks that's what matters.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch's courts because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
The rehearsals of this year began in June, and on the first day almost 30 actors, a dozen whites, and the rest of the blacks, gathered in the room and listened to a re-enacted review of the play over the years.
Wade Marbo was a director with Greene.
He's been the chief member of the clan for years, but he says the role hasn't gotten any easier.
"I feel like I'm dirty because I'm not the man I am," Marbo says.
"But I think it's very important to remember this story because we don't want to go back at the time."
In the room, the actors Darius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, are repeating their roles.
Spectal starts with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Shouting Rascon in return.
It's a blow.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) is laughing.
Green laughs loudest.
"What's the matter," asks Ascon.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I overdoing it?
"No," says Green through laughter.
"I just don't think the whites used to say 'nigga'."
"Yes, yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You've got to read the solid "r."
And there's also a change in the energy in the room: the discomfort changes from a sense of partnership.
Everything has to be done right, not just for the play, but for the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Rascona says the "N" word, it's clear and sharp.
No man laughs.
The show ends cruelly and quickly.
Shouting, shooting, and then silence.
The woman in the mourning black dress stands above the bodies of the actors and sings Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards away, half a hundred viewers wipe out tears and sweat.
There are almost equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to watch the show; many live close by.
They've all endured Georgia's heavy perfume for almost eight hours while Brooks took them on a pilgrimage to Malcolm and Dorsey's graves.
Until then, the murders were only a story, but now that they're standing in the same spot where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are in the air.
When the last note of the song fades, Greene invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend over to their heads, touch blood paint, and static bodies, whispering to each other.
"They're not really dead," one little boy mumbles to remind himself of that.
In a few minutes, Greene is thanking the audience, and suddenly it's over.
Actors drop ropes off the neck and wipe tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main puppet.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional burden of the play finally came upon him.
"It's all right," one of the women whispers.
"We know your heart is good.
You had your reasons."
Later, the audience sits down for dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta livelyly discuss a play with a black couple they just met.
