New results of tests to assess the age of asylum-seekers in Sweden have been published
Recent tests of asylum-seekers in Sweden, which had been subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, showed that more than 80 per cent of those tested had been assessed as persons over 18 years of age, but not all trusted the accuracy of those results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedianalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age estimate of asylum more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, the Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensics agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent of the (2002) testees were rated as 18 years or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensics agency estimated that the test was "probably 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was “probably under 18”.
Tests are conducted only in cases where the age of the person is in doubt.
According to Johann Görancen of the forensics agency, the results are consistent with those of the past months.
“We don’t see a big difference in the statistics from the past months, the numbers are quite the same,” he said to The Local portal.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, “most likely, the age of the test is 18 years or more.”
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, a person had openly declared that 18 of them would be performing this year.
The method of conducting a medical age assessment, which is to X-ray wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and test them for dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Caroline Institute of Claude Marcus, whose work is to assess the biological maturity of humans to determine whether they have reached puberty earlier or later than normal.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don't think I should use the measurement methods that are being used.
The biological age is defined in this way very imprecisely.
If we can't determine it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can, he said to Metro.
However, Göranssen of the forensics agency argued in favour of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, it can be said that the risk of mistaking a child for an adult is small.
