The President will determine the order and place of the oath.
Where and how new Russian citizens will pledge allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have been drafted by the State Committee on Legislation and State Building.
As early as a week ago, deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath of office in the law.
Children under the age of 18, as well as those incompetent, will be exempted from taking a solemn oath, as follows from the revised text of the amendments to the draft law on citizenship of the Russian Federation (as contained in the “Izvestya”) which the committee will consider on 11 July before its second reading at its meeting.
President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of swearing in Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents on 6 June during a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The members of Parliament have incorporated this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the revocation of the decision to grant citizenship to those who have subsequently been convicted of a number of terrorist or extremist offences: for example, public incitement to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (article 205.2, paragraph 2), as well as the hijacking of an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if the act is related to terrorism (article 211, paragraph 4, of the Criminal Code).
According to the bill, the logic of the bill was that, by issuing citizenship documents, a person signed a promise to comply with Russian law - by embarking on the path of extremism, he broke that promise.
In April, the draft law was submitted to the State Duma by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev (“Uniform Russia”), Gennady Zuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (“Just Russia”) and the Speaker of DG Viacheslav Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies accepted it on first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Building and Legislation approved the text of the bill for a second reading, but it has now been reworked.
It now states that the President of the Russian Federation will take the oath of office.
Previously, parliamentarians had intended to describe the procedure directly in the Law on Citizenship of the Russian Federation, stating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the State coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event was to take place, a list of places where the coat of arms of the Russian Federation could be placed, is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include the courts, the offices of the heads of State of the entities, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, the heads of the federal executive, etc.
Most likely, it could also be a registry.
The solemn oath will be given to those wishing to acquire Russian citizenship after the officials have checked their documents.
But the Russian passport will be obtained only after the swearing-in, as follows from the finalized text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text states that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, not the age of 14.
The rule remains that persons with disabilities or limited legal capacity, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath themselves, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt “others” from this procedure.
The updated bill also lays down a special procedure for the admission to Russian of Ukrainian citizens who are considered Russian speakers.
They will have to formally renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting the relevant application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application would need to be handed over to Russian officials.
A waiver of “foreign” nationality, as at present, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible “for reasons beyond the control of the individual”.
A corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among them the first Vice-Speaker of DG Ivan Melnikov (CRPF), Natalia Poclonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all “One Russia”).
I think a lot of you know it's not realistic to get a certificate from Ukraine, it's just impossible.
Consequently, a great many people are waiting for their fate to be decided about Russian citizenship, explained the previous day the head of the State Building and Legislation Committee of the Duma, Pavel Krascheninnikov (ER).
In addition, the text made it clear that restrictions on the holding of certain posts for foreigners would not apply to those who had renounced “other” citizenship in writing and had deposited an old passport with the Ministry of Internal Affairs, but “for reasons beyond its control” he had not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Foreigners are now prohibited from holding municipal posts and from being recruited to work in facilities and organizations whose activities relate to the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit from another country may not become a member of the State Duma or a member of the Council of Federation.
It is planned that the law will enter into force on 1 September 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws will be ready.
