Judges are offered protection from presidents.
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (CHR), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has drawn up proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes that the powers of the presidents of the courts be limited and that they be elected.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts which will not be linked to the administrative division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit proposals within the framework of a presidential mandate.
HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
The HRC conducted this work on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the council.
At a meeting with the council on 8 December 2016, some cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as well as problems of public control in places of detention (see “IU” of 9 December).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals that deal both with the independence of the judiciary and the detection of judicial errors and with the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court presidents to increase the independence of the remaining judges.
If the candidate for the post of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judiciary, the HRC is of the view that the president of the court should submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed that the President be deprived of the right to allocate cases to judges.
This can be done by experts, by means of a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled to “prejudicate the results of a judge's qualification, initiate disciplinary proceedings against him or her, and decide on additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to “the election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and to “ensure their powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation”.
All the presidents of the courts (from the Republic to the District) are now appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize appeals and cassations in the ordinary courts.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative division into the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that “it is necessary to ensure that separate courts of appeal and cassation are not organized at the level of the regional courts in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
The experts are based on the practice of arbitral tribunals.
They have “judicial districts” which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials who are hampered by the use of “telephone rights”.
The HRC proposes that the magistrates be strengthened by people's assessors to deal with certain “classes of civil and administrative cases” with their participation.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honour and dignity, deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"It's just our suggestions," explained HRC member, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara Morchashkov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate referred not only to the HRC but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
The armed forces (among the co-authors, the Office of the Procurator-General and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) still have time to carry out their task.
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the President of the Russian Armed Forces, Vyacheslav Lebedev, is due before 1 September.
Living a high life: semi-storeys and crafty designers have turned this little apartment into a big house in Earls Court.
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is located on the ground floor of a pretty Queen Anne model house, and in favour of a new design, it says that Joan didn't pack her things and move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger square,” Joan says.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were just as high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price on the same day.”
Since the first look, a 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally, it was an apartment with one bedroom of complex design – to get into the bedroom, it had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and floor space to squeeze out the maximum benefit from the bountiful ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
That was my demand," she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill architectural design studio, Duke & Shed, to use the ceilings of 12.5 feet high and create a home that would not only be a successful project but would be worth Joan's life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-storey where one could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the brift.
“Work with steel structures is very complex,” he explains.
“We had to place the premises so that they were one above the other, and we did not have to bend.
It was not simply necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they would be at the right height and allow the use of rooms from above and below.”
This decision allowed Erfan to have two full-sized rooms one above the other in space -- and a lot more interesting.
From the semi-storey through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius", a view of the gorgeous living room below is opened.
Mirror furniture with gold trim, silver accents, and vintage lighting from Serge Muy set the design style.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding visual appearance, width, and light.
The short corridor is surrounded by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror shield looks like a window in the other room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinets are used to store all of Joan's dishes.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block itself in the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new in the folding kitchens.
The unique thing about this kitchen is that it's a moving door up like a garage.
“The engineering art was involved here,” Erfan tells of the steel-reinforced fibre-fibrous shield door.
"It has a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily."
Due to the prudent use of space and storage facilities, Joan obtained an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom and improved layout.
“In the end, floor space is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your real estate is worth,” Erfan says.
"To put it bluntly, the real estate agent will enter and make calculations based on the floor area."
Here, they were able to increase the area of the floor by using quality materials that provide a shade of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the house,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't hurt the strings of our hearts."
This is evidence that, through good design and increased metering, an apartment can turn from something ordinary to something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
