The Public Prosecutor ' s Office believes that the crime cannot be allowed to go unpunished in order not to set a precedent for other HIV-dissidents.
The case against a woman resident of Tumeni was brought under article 109, paragraph 1, of the Criminal Code (cause of death by negligence) in April, following the death of her three-year-old daughter from HIV infection.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
“The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that there was no HIV infection”, was explained by the Prosecutor's Office of the Tyumen Region.
The criminal case was brought before the Kalininsky Rayde of Tumeni, who decided on 25 July to terminate it.
The request was made by the deceased girl's father, who explained that “simplicised the wife, had no complaints against her, made amends and apologized”.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office did not accept the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be quashed and referred to a new hearing.
The girl died, and it's impossible to make up for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-positive mother refused to examine the baby and treat her with a dangerous infection, contrary to the recommendations of the doctors,” reported to the press service of the Public Prosecutor's Office.
In the view of the supervisory authority, it should be punished, otherwise other HIV-dissidents would follow suit.
As reported at the Tumen AIDS Centre, about 12 children living with HIV in the Tyumensk region are now not receiving medical care because of the refusal of their parents.
“And this situation has already improved — during the year of the special group’s work, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat their children with HIV changed their mind — allowed them to diagnose, began taking medication,” said the spokesperson for the AIDS Centre, Elena Losheva.
She said that parents could not be affected by legislation and that, as a result, not all HIV-infected children could be found - mothers were prevented from examining them, hiding and running away from hospitals.
The Risks of HIV Dissidents
At the end of last year, peterburgian sociologists presented the results of the first study of the so-called HIV-dissident movement in Russia.
HIV-dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Medical practitioners and AIDS service activists in NCBs call such views anti-medical, and their distribution is considered to be a serious threat.
