The Gypsies crossed the moat and returned to the street of the millionaires.
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midland are once again in conflict with the determined Gypsies, who have overcome the moats dug by the municipal authorities to retake the field near their homes.
The Gypsies parked 20 houses on wheels in a field bordered by the wealthy Sollihallah street, which was dubbed "millionaire street".
By bringing horses, babies, and many houses on wheels, they returned after being expelled as late as May, and were not prevented by a moat dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their invasion.
This tactful company found a breach in the defensive structures and squeezed its vehicles through a section that was left uninsured to leave space for the trail.
Angry residents attacked the municipality of Sollihalla, saying that he was “incompetent to solve the problem.”
An anonymous local woman said, "They came here on Monday night after being driven out of Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by."
The municipality should be ashamed and forced to act because it is completely incapable of solving the problem.
The gypsies were here in May, they got kicked out, and now they're back.
There were more gypsies last night, and maybe more today.
“The Municipality of Birmingham knows how to solve this problem, they receive long-term court orders to protect their parks”, she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don't like that I keep paying municipal tax, and the municipality can't even stop it.”
A local resident who wanted to remain anonymous said, "It's funny, we just saw these gypsies leave the previous time, and here we are, please, continuing this attack."
This time there were more of them, and we even saw a horse plowing on the meadow.”
The representative of the municipality of Sollihalla said, “We know about the illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and we are cooperating with the Sollihal police; we are taking the necessary legal action to expel them as soon as possible”.
To help us collect evidence, it is very important that as many local residents as possible report any antisocial or criminal behaviour to the police by telephone 101.
This gives us an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
Crimea is operated by the New Light Champagne Wine Plant.
The “New Light Champagne Wine Plant” of the Republic of Crimea has decided to act by transforming the Champagne Wine Plant “New Light” into the OAO, following an order from the Minister of Property and Land Relations of Crimea Anna Anuhina.
100% of the company's shares will remain in Crimea's state ownership.
The registered capital of the joint stock company will be 595.5 million roubles and will consist of 5.955 million ordinary shares with a nominal value of 100 roubles each.
The Ministry of Agriculture of Crimea stated that if funds were not available to upgrade the plant within the next three years, the plant would be at risk of being stopped.
The wear and tear of property, plant and equipment is in the range of 60-70 per cent.
In order to modernize the enterprise, 1.2 billion roubles are needed. Due to its organizational and legal nature, it is obliged to pay 50 per cent of the income to the budget.
What remains is not enough to implement the modernization plan.
“To get money from the owner is problematic, to talk about attracting loans from large credit organizations,” said the heads of the Crimea Mincelhos Sergei Petlin in April this year.
The Crimea Parliament included the enterprise in the privatization forecast for 2017.
It was suggested that it be held and tendered.
The Interfax source in Crimea authorities estimated the possible sale value of the business at $40 million, the investor's investment in modernization at another $30 million.
The New Light in 2016 increased the production of sparkling wines by 2.8 per cent compared to 2015 levels, to 1.52 million bottles.
In 2017, the New Light intended to release 1.6 million bottles.
The company was founded in 1878 by Prince Lion Golitsyn as a factory for the production of sparkling wine in his newly acquired estate.
The plant is located on 11 hectares of land.
