Italy is tightening its tone with regard to NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy warned NGOs that owned rescue vessels in the Mediterranean Sea that they would not be able to continue working unless they complied with the new regulations governing their activities.
“If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” said Interior Minister Mario Minniti in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
The warning to Minnity came the day after the Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had been working for only one year, refused to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Cartozio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain a top priority, so we very much regret that we cannot continue our search and rescue activities now," says the organization's statement on social media.
"We can only assess all the charges now made after we have gathered all the information and we can assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventa ship belonging to the Jugend Rettet since October.
His crew is suspected of taking migrants on board with their lifeboats, who were sent directly to them by traffickers, and of allowing smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place only 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, as alleged in the charges, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the area, more from humanitarian zeal than from any other motive.
The Code of Conduct assumes mainly that the YVV vessels will have on board an Italian police officer who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the “Save the Children”, the Maltese MOAS and the “Pro-Activa Open hug” from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new regulations unnecessary but acceptable, provided that they did not entail any “significant change or interference” with its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign was the Nobel Prize-winning Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minnity said that the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicated that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and cooperation with local mayors were bearing fruit.
"In the last days we started to see the light at the end of the tunnel," said the minister.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
