The Russian Federation authorities have recently significantly stepped up their policy on the Libyan track, and the delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have been involved in visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian Contact Group for the Intra-Livian Settlement under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, the assistant head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Deng, told "I".
The contact group on Libya, which you are chairing, is hardly known.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine, everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The Contact Group was established at the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Her activities are overseen by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delemhanov.
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma, Viacheslav Volodin.
The start of the group was the detention in Libya of a Russian tanker, the Mechanic Chebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board).
We've been thinking about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, was established and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How come you're the one who took over?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been approached to lead the work of the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanic.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict, and with Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government is based, led by Faiz Saraj.) and Tobruk (a parliament that opposes the Government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls eastern Libya.
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Libya Vice Prime Minister), we were able to quickly agree to release Russian sailors.
It was then agreed to establish a contact group to make better use of those contacts.
Its task is to analyse the situation, identify key factors and players, and engage in dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I wish to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to associate ourselves with any of the parties to the conflict; we are engaged in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group, and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
The contact group now includes five persons.
Among them are people with experience in the security forces, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also wish to include in the regional team the representatives of the RA Institute of the Middle East.
No one of our staff is permanently present in Libya; this is not yet necessary.
Are there Russian military advisers, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are untrue.
But your contact group has ex-military members...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we visit hot spots.
Or such closed cities as Misrata (where militia groups are based, which played a role in overthrowing Libyan leader Muammar Qadhafi in 2011 and which have increased markedly in subsequent years).
We arrived in Misrata in January this year.
We were scared, told it was all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who was responsible for what the rumours were about, what was really the role of Islamists.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the forces that were involved in the destruction of the IG in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was taken away from militants of the banned “Islamic State” in Russia.
We wanted to see them, to meet these people, to verify that they were the ones who played a decisive role in the destruction of IGs in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these services to himself.
And what did you come to?
The Islamic State in Libya didn't win Haftar?
He didn't do it.
Haftar was operating on another front, Benghazi.
IGs in Sirte were fought by structures subordinate to the Government in Tripoli.
And by the way, we've invited the people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they came -- the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, and the Libyan delegation was received by the Federation Council, Duma, MIDE and Rosgvardiya.
You, as we understand it, are present in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the moods of local elites and warlords.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire arrangements that were reached in late July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or, again, as has happened many times in the past, agreements will be broken, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to take power alone?
The fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting was a good signal for us, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have been very negative about each other.
And as for Russia's position...
Moscow’s active support for Haftar is often written and spoken of, and many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and Khaftar was on that very day on board a Russian aircraft carrier, Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But Misrata wasn't believed in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people to come to us today."
But our task is precisely to show that we do not support only Haftar; we are engaged in dialogue with all key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar have been in touch.
Does understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level make it easier for him to study twice in the USSR?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, it's very relative.
But the fact that he learned from us makes it easier to have a dialogue with him, of course.
And by the way, it's not just him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who were either in Russia or still in the Soviet Union.
And here they are speaking Russian very well.
And reaching out to Russia, feeling a little nostalgic about it.
Do you consider it likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya would be lifted as soon as possible?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Of course they are, but, as I said, we are not taking sides in this conflict, and we would not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be about equal.
With regard to the arms embargo, Libyans have consistently called for the Russian Federation to contribute to its lifting.
The constitution-making process is now well under way in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then the elections must take place, as was also mentioned at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and legitimate power is finally elected (and none of the parties now has such status), the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised at the United Nations.
It is pointless and dangerous to raise this issue now; it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
There was news in the media the other day that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees from Libya, felt abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners by using its ties with Libyans in this situation?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar troops will take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
That's a very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia’s support, because Moscow has a dialogue with both Haftar and Saraj and Misurata and the south of the country.
Tribes in southern Libya play a major role in this matter, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it a matter of Southerners stopping the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
So, on a conditional basis, you turned back the buses that Nigerian migrants were taking?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in seeing these flows continue.
We hope to help bring southerners together in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The Head of Government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered to be an Islamist supporter of the country ' s Sharia.
How radical is he?
Would that not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give you my personal opinion of him.
In my view, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but it is his position that Libya must be a perfectly normal country, a moderate Islamic, open world.
And he is also active in the fight against terrorists.
How does he have such a reputation?
It was created by countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial branches are located.
There's a national oil corporation, a national bank, and other government structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
And we mixed up all the maps and started to communicate actively with both Tripoli and Tobrooke.
We are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with the Libyan State Oil Company - NOC.
The director of NOC, Mustafa Sanallah, with whom Rosnefti Head Igor Sechin made a deal, was himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess I'll resell it.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign Muammar Qadhafi contracts.
These include previous agreements in the transport field (rail construction), energy (electricity) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, as in the case of Iran, is this about the oil-for-service scheme?
I don't know what the pattern is, I don't deal directly with these issues.
In fact, Russia’s economy in Libya is not the main one.
We are essentially in the peacekeeping business there.
Our main concern is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya is no longer a propitious environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, that is the main objective: to help the Libyan people and to expel terrorists from there.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical fighters from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that, to date, none of the Russians and other countries of the former USSR were there.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya) and no Russian speech.
Which States are these fighters from?
I wouldn't want to go into those details.
Then let's put it another way.
How many of the Islamist fighters in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are virtually no Libyans, not more than 5% of them.
The rest are from here.
Could Moscow hold intra-Lebanese talks like Paris?
There are plans.
We have been engaged in intensive negotiations with Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow and have indicated their willingness to come again to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits are yet to take place, and I hope that the timing and venue of the talks will be clarified.
