Michel Carter's conviction for the reports that prompted Conrad Roy's suicide.
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for inciting her boyfriend Conrad Roy to suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months in prison and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on 13 July 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday, "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum of 20 years, but her lawyers stated that both she and Roy were suffering from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the judgment standing up, with her hands pressed and her eyes lowered.
"By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," said the prosecutor to the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She didn't admit responsibility," she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case that she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his view, her “age, maturity or even mental illness did not have a noticeable impact on her actions”.
The Prosecutor read out the statements of Roy Lynn Roy's mother, which said, "No day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I handle it - I'm trying to support his sisters despite all the pain that's going to stay with us forever," it says.
Sister Roy Kamdin Roy said that she was indistinguishable about the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"The man who's been with me ever since I was born is the pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would make it an offence to advise a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident caught the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been prompted to commit suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife." She wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she killed herself, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad," and, "You just need to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted attention with Roy's death, and he banned her from talking to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
The views of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
30-year-old Knox published a separate opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which stated, "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
