Astronomers have found a hell of a planet where even iron can melt.
After first examining the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysics was surprised by its temperature, which can evaporate iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so heated by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Telescope captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature makes the water in the planet's atmosphere glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b is one of the so-called hot Jupiters, which are gas giants in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the solar system, but located dozens of times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, the exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "earth" days, and its gas envelope is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and Southern France, but it is now feared that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender has grown worse because of dry weather and insect diseases; this has caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert from the CREEPAM Agricultural Research Institute in Provence, says, "Lavanda in Provence is indeed at risk because in recent years the plant has experienced the effects of climate change: the rains in the spring and especially in the autumn have been much smaller.
It affects the length of life of the lavender.
And there are little cicadas jumping through the leaves, carrying microbacteria; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is much needed in perfumery and cosmetics.
Eric Shes says, "Instead of very long ears with many large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened, or absent.
That's why we have fewer parts containing ether oil."
The solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from soil, as well as spraying of plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and the development of more drought-resistant varieties.
