It's a resemblance: an artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA.
In the middle of the hall at the Freedman Gallery in New York City, faces of people, white, black and brown, all of which are elusively similar to each other, hang from the ceiling on the wire.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey Harborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Levenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving 35 years for a famous broadcast of confidential diplomatic cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is called The Exposition of Similarity.
This is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey Harborg, whose art unites technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transsexual woman and a famous dissident, to whom Barack Obama reduced his sentence just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analysing the DNA obtained from Manning and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of individuals who might have such a genome, Dewey Harborg created a profound, albeit difficult, manifesto about not only the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the ingenious determinism of these interpretations - but also the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born under the name Bradley Edward, but when she was a teenager, openly said she thought she was a woman, was sentenced to 20 episodes in 2013, including six violations of the espionage act, computer fraud, and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one of her photographs was known: a grained black and white selfie, in which Manning, in platinum shade, was wearing a wig, apparently uncomfortable, sitting behind the wheel of a car, and was associated with that photograph.
In 2015, Dewey Harborg successfully completed his 2012 "Vision of Strangers".
In it, the artist painted portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," explained Dewey-Hagborg at a preliminary screening of a new press exhibit.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait of her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her prison muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters over a period of two years.
They even wrote a book of "Depressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, who depicted how in the future the president would ease Chelsea's punishment and be able to visit the exhibition in person.
Obama’s decision to release Manning just a few days after the book’s release was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something deep and strong that the exhibition is opening right now, when Donald Trump declares war on people who reveal secret information in the government and invents new ways to stir up animosity on Twitter that he's supposed to mitigate.
When Dewey Harborg was asked about the timing of this, she said, "There's no such thing as an accident."
In the artist's statement written on the wall of the gallery, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of the "i" in her name) calls for an end to “automatic separation based on sex, race, sexual orientation and culture”.
On the other side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar made out of pencils C, G and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist is scientifically elegantly expressed), Dewey Harborg hoped to show how amazingly similar we are, at least in our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome does not define what we are, how open genetic data are for interpretation and how subjective it is,” Dewey Harborg said; her 2007 video work, False Memories, is also displayed here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition, which was in one room, is the above-mentioned novel in comic books.
It features a King Kong-style Manning over the United States Correctional House with a loudspeaker in its hand.
"If they kill your speech, they'll win," it says.
"So never shut up."
"This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me," says the artist welcoming us from Philadelphia.
"I still get goose bumps when I talk about it."
Manning hasn't seen the exhibition in person - as it's been seen in the comic books - but when she comes, she'll be welcomed by the masks in the middle of the room, her own genomic simulations, gathered like crowds of protesters.
It's also done intentionally, like everyone at an exhibition up to height (5", height Manning), where a pencil drew genetic haplogroups.
"I would have hung them on walls earlier, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey Harborg says about portraits.
"I wanted them to look like a mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like a movement that stood behind her release."
