Russian Vice Prime Minister Mutko: "We will meet the requirements of the WADA road map in the near future."
Russian Vice-Premier Vitaly Mutko said that the terms of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) set for the resumption of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) would be fulfilled shortly.
“A certain stage of compliance has been completed, RUSADA has been given the right to plan and conduct tests in conjunction with UKAD (the British Anti-Doping Agency).
WADA's road map was updated accordingly," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Prime Minister commented on the second part of the WADA road map for restoring compliance with the Code, which listed the conditions for the resumption of RUSADA and had recently been published on the organization ' s website.
According to Mutko, it contains nothing that could present difficulties for Russia.
"Everything has been announced, everything will be done.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
However, one of the requirements included in the list implies that Russian Andidoping structures should publicly accept the results of an investigation commissioned by WADA by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren, alleging that doping in Russian sports is controlled by the state.
On this point, Mutko said, “We are investigating because our anti-doping system has malfunctioned.
All measures have been taken.
But there was no government program, and we're not going to admit what didn't happen."
Mutko repeated the words of Vitaly Smirnov, head of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
The same morning, in an interview with Rsport, Smirnov acknowledged earlier problems in Russian anti-doping structures, but added: “We have repeatedly said that the report contains certain controversial positions and provisions.
No one is going to accept this report without reservation," added Smirnov.
WADA suspended RUSADA from conducting doping controls in November 2015 after a doping scandal.
However, in June of this year, it was allowed to plan and coordinate testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
Following a visit to the organization's Moscow office in July, the Director-General of WADA, Olivier Niggley, stated that RUSADA was “going in the right direction” to restore its work.
