Startups that will help your company not to become another Uber
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among his startup e-commerce staff, but the polls didn't work.
Answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
Even though she promised anonymity, some staff members did not trust the process.
“He has never been consistent and objective,” Herrett told the manager of a 75-person company in San Francisco, Madison Reed, which deals in hair-care e-commerce.
She therefore sought the assistance of others.
A new type of staff start-up is now emerging that helps companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure staff involvement, they allow companies to conduct rapid interviews, address certain teams and demographic groups, offer staff anonymity and hotlines for complaints and, in some cases, allow informants to pass through top management and direct contact with management.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint launch shop in Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Herrett said that she had gained a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in three years of use of Glint.
In addition to the express interviews and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers the company's thermal map and shows in visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows them to understand why.
Companies are a little aware that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber involved in a scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who were disgruntled were punished.
For start-ups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable business.
The Internet portal, “Let's talk about payment”, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation and conformity industry could cost over $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Convercent launch from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies to prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year in the face of the fall in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber became a client.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send individually commissioned staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text hotline that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager is involved, the complaints go straight to the board.
“The Court of Public Opinion seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company finds itself ill-treated or unethical, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of client boycotts, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with over 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, used Convercent for over a year to make sure that employees were aware of the rules and procedures and to suggest a simple way to contact the company's head office.
In the past, if the staff member wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or an e-mail from the head office, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, the head of the legal department of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to track staff complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that used to be hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and dealt with.
“I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the staff situation,” said Vitrano, who leads the risk management team of the Ruby Tuesday network.
“And we protect our shareholders from legal proceedings against employees.”
According to Queensland, companies began to take staff ethics, values and involvement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed due to ethical irregularities as a result of Dela Enron.
But it was only when social media became widespread that companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution online.
“Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly for the use of their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has been endorsed by venture capitalists who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from companies such as the Sapphire Ventures and the Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessmer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than before.
In markets with strong competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, this is just the minimum.
Staff members want to feel that they are accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to companies with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work for the company, they feel they are heard, and the work they do results, they try more to make the company successful,” says Nina McQueen, Vice President for Global Benefits and Staff Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies do well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the commitment and involvement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to cultural experts in the workplace, it is important to have data on the involvement of employees.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks staff for feedback, it may give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not happen quickly enough, or at all, frustration may develop, and the staff will lose interest.
“If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be ready to have 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rat, president of Kotter International’s management consulting firm, who had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Herrett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly staff interviews, is in a position to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem through Glint.
And after collecting feedback from staff dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge of its employees and hopes that in the long run this knowledge will help it to better retain staff in an industry known for high turnover.
“If you do not try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose clients.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
