Create a comic novel: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scottney's tiny castle was filmed in a music video called "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a home for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy spot in the Bühl Valley in Kent County, he watched a violent story around him, and now he inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with smoked hair and a propensity for historical documents, for a novel comic book.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel it in person when you hold this letter in your hand."
"The Castle in England" covers the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about families who lived in Scotland; each story was illustrated by a young British artist, Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer, and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man's Tooths and Other Stories, a compilation of British Library documents; this project suddenly touched him deeply.
"I could have been touched by a thumbprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for Jacobites," he says.
"It's his thumbprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those times, the lights were lit.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there, too.
Oh, I love archives!"
For a man who is so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months ("I'm a little bit caught up in it") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle all day long, walked through the archives, and looked at numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things, such as the heads of hyenas on walls or bottles that had been in the pit for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to rangers, gardeners, and sometimes artists working on illustrations of his book.
Then at night, he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of the castle is not very well understood, because the National Foundation did not gain full access to it until 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassie, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, staff were just beginning to deal with the archive he described as "that the aristocrats have been thrown into the attic for centuries."
Books, British Empire letters, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but this bereza was fought by two families.
It happens like that, guys!"
In some of the compilation's stories, the castle becomes the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in "Worker", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the 1381 Peasant Revolution.
“There is evidence of a riot that took place at the castle in 1380, in a book called the Knights' Families of Kent and Sussex,” Rhodes says.
"The Bristian rebellion started in these places, and I thought the riot was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are strongly related to the history of the castle, such as the Priest, which tells of the Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family has been hiding for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Smuggler," about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have faked his own funeral by stone-throwing a coffin (which was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are Rhodes's favorite family who inhabited Skotney: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect con artist, always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I imagine them as a company of handsome men who can care for the heirs of great fortunes."
After finishing his job at Castle Rhodes is looking for other ways to get a unique writing experience.
He lived two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamyanmäki, a place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it grew back into forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: Hell, I have to go back to real life again."
The top 15 banks choose Rossia.
The conflict in the Association of Russian Banks (ARB) is developing: following Sberbank, WTB, WTB-24, Alpha Bank, Gazprombank, Rosselhozbank, Binbank and FK Open, seven other credit organizations are about to leave this public organization.
Thus, no less than 80 per cent of the market will be accounted for by organizations that have withdrawn from the ARB.
But this is not just a solution - all banks that have declared a break with the ARB are negotiating with another public organization that brings together credit institutions, the Association of Regional Banks “Russia”, which is headed by a well-known politician, Anatoly Aksakow, the Chairman of the Financial Market Committee of the State Duma, recognized, by the last session, and the most effective head of the Duma Committee and the deputy in terms of the number of bills drafted.
The conflict within the ARB began during the discussion in the Federation Council, when new bills were considered by the Interregional Banking Council, including a new classification of banks according to the size of the statutory capital.
At that time, Garegin Tosunyan, President of the ARB, stated that the association believed that the bill was being passed for the benefit of the largest banks, which were thus trying to limit the capacity of small and medium-sized banks in the regions by intercepting their clients.
Other claims included criticism of the Central Bank, which, according to Tosunyan, does not always justify withdrawing licences from some banks, but was objected to by a representative of the Central Bank: many of the directors of the banks that were involved, such as Vnesprombank, were members of the governing bodies of the ARB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive views in a highly sensitive relationship with the main regulator of the banking environment has become a visible reason for the 15 largest banks to start preparing for membership of the Association “Russia” in opposition to the ARB policy, noting that “the effectiveness of the ARB will be low and that constructive dialogue within the banking community is virtually non-existent”.
The depositors will be better off.
How's this gonna end?
Answer immediately the main question that arises in or around the slightest banking breakdown or conflict: depositors are not at risk, but rather the credibility of the banking system will be improved.
Anatoly Aksakov, known for his sensitivity to the interests of banks and their clients, is a high-level professional who is highly valued in the Central Bank: virtually all the CBs are present at the annual activities of the association, and all significant legislative initiatives of the regulator are carried out through expert evaluations of the “regions”.
In terms of personnel and organization, it is also clear that there are no major disruptions.
There is no doubt that the ARB is in a difficult financial and managerial situation once such powerful and influential actors, with their contributions and lobbying capabilities, are dispossessed.
However, this oldest, established in 1991, has considerable potential to further improve banking legislation and monetary management in general.
Nor can it be said that Russia, with open arms, is prepared to accept new members on any terms, based on the reaction of its leader, Anatoli Aksakova (“may be too eager”), who, as early as 21 July at a briefing at the Parliamentary Newspaper press centre, stated that “the next day, the representatives of the ARB banks asked me to consider developing the potential of our association, Roscia”.
Their proposals are to strengthen the voice of bankers in the Association Council, as well as to pay more attention to new banking technologies.
A negotiating process is under way, proposals from both sides are being studied, and an extraordinary congress of the association is being prepared, to be held in Sochi in mid-September in the framework of an international banking forum.
That's where we'll figure it out.
Also, Anatoly Aksakow, stressing that “the chair does not hold,” described the possible new leader of the newly revamped association “Russia” Giorgi Luntovsky, who is leaving the post of Vice-President of the Central Bank in September, with a high profile of his business and human qualities.
