Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help to ease the HCC.
Red meat and chocolate are commonly considered nightmares for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: diets rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate the symptoms of those suffering from inflammatory intestinal diseases.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to colics and abdominal swelling, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
In general, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of triptophan protein contributes to the production of immune cells that enhance intestinal tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells in the intestines ensured that malignant germs from food did not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of launching an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the equilibrium is too severe to inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines develop more tolerant cells.
And this bacteria needs a triptophane -- one of the building blocks of a protein -- to trigger these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We've established a connection between one type of bacteria -- Lactobacillus reuteri -- which is part of a normal microbioma of the intestine, and the development of a population of cells that enhance tolerance.
The more tryptophane was fed to the mice, the more immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich triptophane diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammable environment in the intestines.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganovas, after studying a variety of tolerant immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line but was held separately had none.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by microbiomas in the intestines of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of mouse intestinal cells has been sequenced, and six types of bacteria present in mice with immune cells but missing in mice without them have been detected.
Mouses grown in sterile environments that did not have a good microbial and that did not develop this type of immune cell received L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then carried small portions of liquid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells separated from mice.
The immune cells have become more tolerant cells.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of triptophane, known as indol-3-minoric acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophane in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophane was halved, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of the L. reuteri triptophane contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as mice, but individuals with inflammatory intestinal diseases have been found to have defects in the genes associated with the triptophane.
She says, "Maybe we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because these cells are the key to inflammatory processes on the inside of the intestines.
High levels of triptophane with L. reuteri have the potential to increase their population.”
