The White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the Armed Forces records given to the magazine "TIME", the decision of the White House last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn to an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president was on board, became a central feature of the White House event on July 17, which featured American construction programmes.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pens, and senior White House officials examined the technology products from all 50 states.
A helicopter produced in Connecticut was shown next to a boat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a Mississippi truck.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the helicopter control department of the White House Military Department ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to make sure that you knew because this is an unusual media event,” wrote HMX-1 commander in an e-mail to his superior, the First Deputy Chief of Marine Corps Aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at around 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return to the flight in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, while security guards remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by TIME whether a second crew was required as a result.
The Hetch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event was in conflict with this regulation.
“We asked, among other things, whether it was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told it wasn't,” the commander wrote.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The event “made in America” was declared the White House as an official event and was not subject to Hatch's law.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health-care reform then in the Senate and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them only in the interests of photo ops.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports complaining about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled by the show “made in America”, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” says Deputy White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often conduct training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to the White House to the nearest inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight for the "Done in America" event was counted to the crew for the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not covered by any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not been involved in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not record the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's rate of reimbursement for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit recorded a 30-minute flight time in the air from each side of its airfield at the Quantico Marine Airbase in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“It is completely wrong to calculate the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement,” Walters says.
“These approximate rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs, which are included in annual allotments.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things done in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose job depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
It is, of course, entirely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump had interacted with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump contacted Shikorsky, making a press joke about his own food fleet.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said. “I have three of them.”
