There will be two new territories in Russia that are leading socio-economic development: Abaza and Novotroitsk.
The relevant decrees of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of the TOR are defined in the territory of the city of Abaza in the Republic of Hakasia.
In a city of 15,000 people, there will be a special legal regime for business activity, as well as a minimum capital investment by residents and a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to attract some 2.5 billion roubles of investment in the city, as well as to generate more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which the special legal regime for business activities will be applied in the Abaza, for example, includes crop production, livestock production, food production, non-alcoholic beverages and clothing.
Already, the Government of the Republic has signed framework agreements for the implementation of eight investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the Territory's dependence on the Abakan mine, a city-making enterprise.
In January 2017, the authorities in the region reported that Hakasia had met all the conditions of the Ministry of Economic Development for the establishment of the TOR.
The authorities of the Orenburg region have also done the same.
There, the town of Novotrotsik will also have an area leading to socio-economic development.
This will diversify the mono-city economy, reduce its dependence on the urbanizing enterprise of Ural steel, and create more than 23,000 jobs and attract investment of more than 8 billion roubles.
The list of economic activities under which the new TOR will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes, inter alia, freshwater fish farming, feed production, medicines and medical supplies.
Novotroitsk was the first monocity in the Orenburg region to be granted the status of TOR.
It should be recalled that a forward-looking territory is an economic zone with preferential tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges that are created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
The following benefits are available to residents of the TOS: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent in the first five years, and at least 10 per cent in the next five years, a social contribution of 7.6 per cent in 10 years, the use of the customs free zone, preferential access to various infrastructure facilities, and preferential rent rates.
